Content:
As in: 
What IF, in Alga (or else), I NOT ONLY:
-  view, manage, trade, and evtl. stake (on) datatoken,

but I ALSO:
- manage "my" dataPFP, 
- browse #Web3 in it (built-in browser like Metamask today),

- manage which data I want to share with which platform OR platform-class

- RealDataWhale = dApp/mobile App skills, community
- DataUnion = dApp skills PLUS Data Union skills, as in: what makes the most valuable data SETS, on micro (individual) and on macro (aggregated , compare above: 2 million social media users) level

- FELTtoken = deep machine learning <-> compute to data skills, as in: what would be the most valuable/efficient data-APIs for eg social media platforms in this example?

Author: wally0221
Content:
Final words:
1.) I am sorry for just throwing this in front of your feed while this could be a complete concept of its own, potentially powerful. Yet, since Ocean Protocol is as big and universal as it is, this is STILL one vertical, one way of bridging where we are at with our Tech as Ocean Protocol and where the crypto space is at.

2.) This is still the best I could do, given the big roadmap OPF has in front of it. So by making it a combined, but still an "integration layer" effort in the ecosystem, I hope that this concept can prosper and create great data supply and demand for Ocean Protocol, while I can still focus on my core tasks at hand and not disappoint either the brilliant visionaries in the team (way greater than me) or the community (both Ocean and DAO)

3.) This is a first in OceanDAO land, afaik. So please treat it as such: it is NOT a core OPF project or effort. It's experimental by me, Wally. I applied my old ecosystem hat thinking from my work in GSMA with Google, Telekom AT&T, etc.

In a different world and time, I would have made this the core strategy flagship, a "speedboat" as they call it. But those times, enterprise, are luckily over! 

In Ocean,  our roadmap is so packed (you know it), I would only have had greenlight to look at this full focus in Q3, but I was so afraid it would be too lated by then. 

SO we do a compromise, Web3 style. I am kickstarting a positive sum game by handing over all my thoughts and the hat over to you instead. The brilliant builders in OceanDAO land. So as always: be open, be supportive, don't own or hide ideas, rather share them openly (10x better) and build components legostyle that work together, towards a first lean, then continously improved UX, also define limits where your bandwidth is exceeded, in general: make us proud, web3 style, hand in hand. üåä‚òØÔ∏èüôå

I will try to come in here, consult, and help develop ideas, but I cannot promise anything. Hope that's ok w/ you.

Author: doteth
Content:
I will jump into the conversation tomorrow morning as it's night here already, but in short I think it's a great idea worth exploring. 

As I was saying to Malte, fact shows that we are VERY late for the NFT hype right now, and BAYC dropping in FP is creating instability in the space. However, a new recent trend (healthier for us too) could be ENS.

I was in a Spaces with ENS founder @avsa and he was saying how overwhelmed the team was about this recent community-driven effort (referring to the 10k club) and so to further drive adoption of ENS (and revenue) they are considering creating the tools to allow the creation of different "NFT collections" within the ENS ecosystem. (10k club, 100kclub, 3letters club, 24h club)

The ENS ecosystem will probably kick off the growth of different collections the same way we saw with OpenSea - in which each collection has their stewards + utlity sort to speak. This is not directly related to Data, but a trend to hook on perhaps.

Lots to discuss and not a clear direction yet, but I agree that PFPs will have stronger utility and could help OP/DataNFTs gain more exposure.

Author: mantisclone
Content:
> unlimited use of training data for a period of time
This is possible using datatokens and wouldn't require the data nft owner to relinquish control of the data nft. When creating the datatoken, specify the `timeout` to be the number of seconds that a given order is valid for. The dataset or algorithm can then be consumed or used for compute-to-data as many times as the consumer wants until the timeout is reached.

> Or to try monetize the data on your behalf?
I could imagine a professional service that runs ocean infrastructure on behalf of a data publisher. This would certainly require some off-chain coordination and trust, but could still be accomplished using datatokens. The datatoken's `service_endpoint` could point to a provider instance run by the ocean infrastructure provider.  The infrastructure provider would collect provider fees while the data nft owner collects order fees.

Author: flowscience
Content:
I've been getting into some interesting conversations about data ownership and IP-NFTs lately. Can data be owned? 

As a DAO launching a fork of Ocean Market we're running into some community concerns about  a potential "staking rush" of people making claims of data ownership & profiting off them when there will definitely be contested claims down the road. Some potential solutions included using verifiable credentials or decentralized identity solutions but there is still a missing link between the IP-NFT and the real world assets (not data) associated with them. 

Here are a couple threads started by Encrypgen that I chimed in on (directly referencing the Ocean Whitepaper in the 2nd thread):
https://twitter.com/Encrypgen/status/1532094137096364033?t=TCduNDzJ0KObHUwTnSrBLA&s=19

Author: Timothy.AthenaProtocol.Eth#2384
Content:
I thought I'd come by and share something pretty exciting that we have been working on over the past few months. 

Athena Protocol is a member organization and founder of dMeter, a dao for the creation of open standards in MRV ( monitoring reporting and verification ) for ESG. This organization has begun to develop its system of governance of these open standards, and Athena Protocol is leading the Engineering Circle, helping to bring adoption of Ocean Protocol Tools and softwares. Our work creating signed claims and comments for the ocean stack has prepared us to compose our middleware's into a data transaction and verification layer capable of conducting audits and certifying ecosystem services. We have a list of organizations planing to integrate with our middleware. 

One organization Im very excited to announce in particular participating in the integrations is the Regen Network ! They will be modifying their attestations to accept IPFS hashes, as well as working with us to develop a shared meta-data schema for v2 of our contracts.  v2 will include geospatial indicators for data assets for easy spatial searches and more!

Author: swish24_08
Content: basically C2D pairs some datasets with an algorithm so that the user never sees the raw data just what the algorithm generates. Ideally you review the algorithms that are allowed on your dataset so that it doesn't just return it. This can work with static datasets and you can team up with someone that creates the algorithm so that both of you can profit. The best use case is with dynamic data (that updates constantly) so the user need to start a c2d job each week or each month depending on how fast the data updates.

Author: jamie123abc
Content:
I'm not sure I fully understand what you are trying to do here? Barge deploys the ocean contracts on ganache and then starts up the other ocean components in docker containers. When you say, "connect to a different ethereum RPC provider" it sounds like you are trying to use a different network? 

If your intention is to use a different testnet, I would highly recommend that you use one of the testnets that we are already deployed to - such as goeli or Mumbai. Barge is not a tool for deploying the contracts to other networks. Normally all contract deployments are handled by the core team.

Author: carmina19
Content: Hello @alex, if you use barge, the contracts are deployed locally on ganache/development network and you need to export the address file (because for ganache the addresses are not persistent) like this `export ADDRESS_FILE=~/.ocean/ocean-contracts/artifacts/address.json`. If you want to use a remote network, you do not need barge.

Author: enzo_vezzaro
Content: Hi @Muthu you need to follow this simple guide to fork the market: https://docs.oceanprotocol.com/building-with-ocean/build-a-marketplace/forking-ocean-market. Once you have done that, you just need to set NEXT_PUBLIC_INFURA_PROJECT_ID on the .env file and you should be able to transact on any network we have available by default. You can use Goerli or Mumbai for testing, just check those networks on the market, and make sure your wallet is connected to one of those testnet. Hope this answers your question, if you need further information, let me know.

Author: Norbert | Ocean#7805

Author: feno1486
Content: Please tell me how can I make my prediction? The bot is running, continuously updated, but I don‚Äôt see in the instructions how to make a predictions?

Author: Norbert | Ocean#7805
Content: You don't have to do anything. If the prediction window it's getting close to be closed, it's going to submit the prediction for you. For example, if you predict 5m timeframe, ~20s before current timeframe is ended it's going to submit.

Author: feno1486
Content: Ah, I understand. You mean that while the bot is running, I participate in predictions automatically. Ok, how can I choose the direction of the predict? I mean whether the price will rise or fall, the amount of money I want to bet on the prediction. I don't quite understand this part

Author: Norbert | Ocean#7805
Content:
For setting the stake amount check the envvars.md file from pdr-backend readmes folder. You have to set the environment variable and then the way that is going to be used depends on the chosen approach.
Right now the predicted value is automatically determined by the approach you are choosing. Approach 1 uses random values while Approach 3 uses a dynamic modal which is trained on past price data and predicts the value for you.
If you want to customize the predicted value you can change on of the approaches.

Author: mertkkl
Content: Hey, does shipyard program only funds retroactive projects or at least in MVP stage? Can i apply the program with detailed proposal with my idea about a dev tooling project?

Author: kreigdk
Content:
Hello @Mert ! Sorry for delay

The Ocean Shipyard program is an early-stage grant program established to fund the next generation of Web3 dApps built on Ocean Protocol. It is designed for entrepreneurs looking to build Web3 solutions on Ocean, make valuable data available, build innovations, and create value for the Ocean ecosystem. Therefore, you should be able to apply to the program with a detailed proposal for your idea about a dev tooling project.
